{"word":"διάκονος","slug":"διάκονος","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>διάκονος</b></el> <br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b>Akin to <a href='S:διάκτορος'><el>διάκτορος</el></a>: both <a href='S:perhaps'>perh.</a> from <el>διώκω.</el>\n<p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><i>a servant, waiting-man</i>, <a href='S:Latin'>Lat.</a> <el>minister</el>, <b><a href='S:Herodotus'>Hdt.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a>: <i>a messenger</i>, <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>:—as <a href='S:feminine'>fem.</a>, <b><a href='S:Demosthenes'>Dem.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b><i>a minister of the church, a deacon</i>, <b><a href='S:New Testament'>NTest.</a></b>: as <a href='S:feminine'>fem.</a> <i>a deaconess</i>, <b><a href='S:New Testament'>NTest.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}